County\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n-->\n<!-- total number of cases is a combination of positive cases, recovered cases and deaths-->\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |5,893\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |99\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |2\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |5,994\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Illinois}}\n* [http://www.dph.illinois.gov/topics-services/diseases-and-conditions/diseases-a-z-list/coronavirus Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) information] from [[Illinois Department of Public Health]]\n* [http://coronavirus.illinois.gov State of Illinois Coronavirus (COVID-19) Response]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Illinois|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Illinois]]\n[[Category:2020 in Illinois|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Health in Illinois]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Mr Xaero", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed date", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Illinois"}
{"title_page": "Ambrosia beetle", "text_new": "'''Ambrosia beetles'''          are beetles of the [[weevil]] subfamilies [[Scolytinae]] and [[Platypodinae]] ([[Coleoptera]], [[Curculionidae]]), which live in nutritional [[symbiosis]] with [[ambrosia fungi]]. The beetles excavate tunnels in dead or stressed trees in which they cultivate fungal gardens, their sole source of nutrition.\nAfter landing on a suitable tree, an ambrosia beetle excavates a tunnel in which it releases [[spore]]s of its fungal symbiont. The fungus penetrates the plant's [[xylem]] tissue, extracts nutrients from it, and concentrates the nutrients on and near the surface of the beetle gallery. Ambrosia fungi are typically poor wood degraders, and instead utilize less demanding nutrients.<ref>Kasson, M.T., Wickert, K.L., Stauder, C.M., Macias, A.M., Berger, M.C., Simmons, D.R., Short, D.P., DeVallance, D.B. and Hulcr, J., 2016. Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles. Fungal Ecology, 23, pp.86-96.</ref> The majority of ambrosia beetles colonize xylem (sapwood and/or heartwood) of recently dead trees, but some attack stressed trees that are still alive, and a few species attack healthy trees.<ref name= Hulcr2017>Hulcr, J. and Stelinski, L.L., 2017. The ambrosia symbiosis: From evolutionary ecology to practical management. Annual Review of Entomology, 62, pp.285-303.</ref> Species differ in their preference for different parts of trees, different stages of deterioration, and in the shape of their tunnels (\"galleries\"). However, the majority of ambrosia beetles are not specialized to any taxonomic group of hosts, unlike most [[phytophagous]] organisms including the closely related [[bark beetle]]s.\nOne species of ambrosia beetle, ''[[Austroplatypus incompertus]]'' exhibits [[eusociality]], one of the few organisms outside of [[Hymenoptera]] and [[Isoptera]] to do so.\n\n==Classification and diversity==\n[[Image:Xylosandrus crassiusculus galleryR.jpg|thumb|left|Gallery of ''[[Xylosandrus crassiusculus]]'' split open, with pupae and black fungus]]\n\nUntil recently ambrosia beetles have been placed in independent families Scolytidae and Platypodidae, however, they are in fact some of the most highly derived [[weevils]], and are now placed in the subfamilies [[Scolytinae]] and [[Platypodinae]] of Family [[Curculionidae]]<ref>Kuschel, G., R. A. B. Leschen, et al. (2000): Platypodidae under scrutiny. Invertebrate Taxonomy 14: 771-805.<br />Marvaldi, A. E., A. S. Sequeira, et al. (2002): Molecular and Morphological Phylogenetics of Weevils (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea): Do Niche Shifts Accompany Diversifcation? Systematic Biology 51(5): 761-785.<br/>Duane D. McKenna, Andrea S. Sequeira, Adriana E. Marvaldi, and Brian D. Farrell. 2009. Temporal lags and overlap in the diversification of weevil and flowering plant. PNAS 106:7083-7088.</ref> There are about 3,000 known beetle species employing the ambrosia strategy.<ref>Hulcr, J., Atkinson, T.H., Cognato, A.I., Jordal, B.H. and McKenna, D.D., 2015. Morphology, taxonomy, and phylogenetics of bark beetles. Bark beetles: biology and ecology of native and invasive species, pp.41-84.</ref>\n\nAmbrosia beetles are an [[Guild (ecology)|ecological guild]], but not a [[Clade|phylogenetic clade]]. The ambrosia habit is an example of [[convergent evolution]], as several groups evolved the same symbiotic relationship independently.<ref>Farrell, B. D., A. S. O. Sequeira, et al. (2001): The evolution of agriculture in beetles (Curculionidae: Scolytinae and Platypodinae). Evolution 55: 2011-2027.</ref> The highest diversity of ambrosia beetles is in the tropics. In the [[Paleotropical]] region, hundreds of species of [[Xyleborini]] and [[Platypodinae]] are the main agent initiating dead wood decomposition. In the [[Neotropic]]s, [[Platypodinae]] and [[Xyleborini]] are joined by the scolytine tribe [[Cortylini]]. Compared to the diversity in the tropics, ambrosia beetle fauna in the temperate zone is rather limited. In the [[Nearctic]] region it is dominated by a few species from Cortylini, Xyleborini and [[Xyloterini]]. In the [[Palearctic]] [[ecozone]], significant groups are Xyloterini and Xyleborini, joined by [[Scolytoplatypodini]] in the Far East.\n\n[[Image:Dinoplatypus chevrolati.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Dinoplatypus chevrolati]]'' from Papua New Guinea, an example of Platypodinae, another species-rich group of ambrosia beetles]]\n\n==The symbiotic relationship==\nBeetles and their [[larva]]e graze on [[mycelium]] exposed on the gallery walls and on bodies called [[sporodochia]], clusters of the fungus' spores. Most ambrosia beetle species don't ingest the wood tissue; instead, the sawdust resulting from the excavation is pushed out of the gallery. Following the larval and pupal stage, adult ambrosia beetles collect masses of fungal spores into their [[mycangium|mycangia]] and leave the gallery to find their own tree.\n\nA few dozen species of ambrosia fungi have been described, currently in the genera ''[[Ambrosiella]]'', ''[[Meredithiella]]'', and ''[[Phialophoropsis]]'' (from [[Microascales]]), ''[[Afroraffaelea]]'' and ''[[Raffaelea]]'' (from Ophiostomatales), ''[[Ambrosiozyma]]'' ([[Saccharomycetales]]), ''[[Fusarium]]'' and ''[[Geosmithia]]'' (from [[Hypocreales]]),  and ''[[Flavodon]]'' (from [[Basidiomycota]]).<ref name= Hulcr2017 /> Many more species remain to be discovered. Little is known about the [[bionomy]] or specificity of ambrosia fungi. Ambrosia fungi are thought to be dependent on transport and inoculation provided by their beetle symbionts, as they have not been found in any other [[habitat]]. All ambrosia fungi are probably [[asexual reproduction|asexual]] and clonal.<ref>Malloch, D., and M. Blackwell. 1993. Dispersal biology of ophiostomatoid fungi. p. 195-206. In: Ceratocystis and Ophiostoma: Taxonomy, Ecology and Pathology. Eds., Wingfield, M.J., K.A. Seifert, and J.F. Webber. APS, St. Paul.</ref> Some beetles are known to acquire (\"steal\") fungal [[pathogen|inoculum]] from fungal gardens of other ambrosia beetle species.<ref>Hulcr, J., Cognato, A. I. 2010. Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles. Evolution, 64 (11): 3205-3212</ref>\n\n==Evolutionary origin==\nDuring their evolution, most scolytid and platypodid weevils became progressively more or less dependent on fungi regularly co-habiting dead trees. This evolution had various outcomes in different groups:\n* Some [[phloem]]-eating bark beetles (phloeophages) are vectors of [[phytopathogen]]ic fungi, which in some cases contribute to tree death.<ref>Paine, T. D., K. F. Raffa, et al. (1997): Interactions between scolytid bark beetles, their associated fungi and live host [[conifer]]s. Annual Review of Entomology 42: 179-206.</ref> The extent to which fungal pathogenicity benefits the beetles themselves is not at all trivial and remains disputed.<ref>Six, D.L. and Wingfield, M.J., 2011. The role of phytopathogenicity in bark beetle\u2013fungus symbioses: a challenge to the classic paradigm. Annual Review of Entomology, 56, pp.255-272.</ref>\n* Many of phloem-feeding bark beetles use phloem-infesting fungi as an addition to their diet. Some phloeophages became dependent on such a mixed diet and evolved [[mycangium|mycangia]] to transport their symbionts from maternal trees to newly infested trees.<ref>Klepzik, K. D. and D. L. Six (2004): Bark Beetle&nbsp;\u2013 Fungal Symbiosis: Context Dependency in Complex Associations. Symbiosis 37: 189-205.</ref> These beetles are called ''mycophloeophages''.\n* Ambrosia beetles and ambrosia fungi are thus only one end of the spectrum of the [[symbiosis|weevil-fungus association]], where both the beetle and the fungus became completely dependent on each other.<ref>Beaver, R. A. (1989): Insect-Fungus Relationship in the Bark and Ambrosia Beetles. Insect-Fungus Interactions. N. Wilding, N. M. Collins, P. M. Hammond and J. F. Webber, Academic Press: 121-143.</ref>\n\n==Impact on forests==\n\nThe vast majority of ambrosia beetles colonize dead trees, and have minor or no economic effect. A few species are able to colonize living stressed trees (Xylosandrus).<ref>Ranger, C.M., Reding, M.E., Persad, A.B. and Herms, D.A., 2010. Ability of stress\u2010related volatiles to attract and induce attacks by Xylosandrus germanus and other ambrosia beetles. Agricultural and Forest Entomology, 12(2), pp.177-185.</ref> A few species are able to attack live and healthy trees, and those can reach epidemic proportions in non-native, invaded regions (''Xyleborus glabratus'', ''Euwallacea fornicatus''<ref>Hulcr, J., Black, A., Prior, K., Chen, C.Y. and Li, H.F., 2017. Studies of ambrosia beetles (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) in their native ranges help predict invasion impact. Florida Entomologist, 100(2), pp.257-261.</ref>).\n\nBeetle species that readily colonize lumber, such as sawlogs, green lumber, and stave-bolts, often cause region-specific economic loss from the pinhole and stained-wood defects caused by their brood galleries. In Northern USA and Canada, conifer logs are attractive to ''Trypodendron lineatum'' (Oliv.) during the spring swarming flight (Dyer 1967).<ref name=\"dye\">Dyer, E.D.A. 1967. Relation of attack by ambrosia beetle (''Trypodendron lineatum'' (Oliv.)) to felling date of spruce in central British Columbia. For. Can., Can. For. Serv., Ottawa ON, Bi-mo. Res. Notes 23(2):11.</ref> Previous studies showed that short log sections become attractive more rapidly than corresponding long logs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Laurel wilt disease]]\n* [[Forest pathology]]\n* ''[[Euwallacea fornicatus]]''\n* ''[[Xyleborus glabratus]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikispecies|Platypodinae}}\n* [http://www.ambrosiasymbiosis.org Images and information] on the Ambrosia Symbiosis at the University of Florida.\n* The [https://web.archive.org/web/20130701003854/http://www.scolytid.msu.edu/ MSU HISL database] contains a worldwide species list of Xyleborini, a major group of ambrosia beetles, from the Catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae of S.L. Wood and D.E. Bright (1992)\n* A USDA-sponsored [http://itp.lucidcentral.org/id/wbb/xyleborini/ information resource and key] to the world genera of Xyleborini\n* [http://www.barkbeetles.info American Bark and Ambrosia Beetles]\n* More information on ambrosia beetle social behaviour and fungiculture on [http://behav.zoology.unibe.ch/index.php?pp=55&p=46]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120422080021/http://www.dontmovefirewood.org/blog/farewell-taco-topping.html Farewell to taco topping?] The effects of the Redbay ambrosia beetle and laurel wilt disease\n* Ambrosia beetles on the [[University of Florida|UF]] / [[Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences|IFAS]] Featured Creatures Web site\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/beetles/platypus.htm ''Platypus'' spp., ambrosia beetles]\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/asian_ambrosia_beetle.htm ''Xylosandrus crassiusculus'', Asian (or granulate) ambrosia beetle]\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/black_twig_borer.htm ''Xylosandrus compactus'', black twig borer]\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* van de Peppel, L. J. J., Aanen, D. K., & Biedermann, P. H. W. (2018). ''[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1754504817301848 Low intraspecific genetic diversity indicates asexuality and vertical transmission in the fungal cultivars of ambrosia beetles]''. Fungal Ecology, 32, 57\u201364.\n\n[[Category:Woodboring beetles]]\n[[Category:Platypodinae]]\n[[Category:Scolytinae]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ambrosia beetles''' are beetles of the [[weevil]] subfamilies [[Scolytinae]] and [[Platypodinae]] ([[Coleoptera]], [[Curculionidae]]), which live in nutritional [[symbiosis]] with [[ambrosia fungi]]. The beetles excavate tunnels in dead or stressed trees in which they cultivate fungal gardens, their sole source of nutrition.\nAfter landing on a suitable tree, an ambrosia beetle excavates a tunnel in which it releases [[spore]]s of its fungal symbiont. The fungus penetrates the plant's [[xylem]] tissue, extracts nutrients from it, and concentrates the nutrients on and near the surface of the beetle gallery. Ambrosia fungi are typically poor wood degraders, and instead utilize less demanding nutrients.<ref>Kasson, M.T., Wickert, K.L., Stauder, C.M., Macias, A.M., Berger, M.C., Simmons, D.R., Short, D.P., DeVallance, D.B. and Hulcr, J., 2016. Mutualism with aggressive wood-degrading Flavodon ambrosius (Polyporales) facilitates niche expansion and communal social structure in Ambrosiophilus ambrosia beetles. Fungal Ecology, 23, pp.86-96.</ref> The majority of ambrosia beetles colonize xylem (sapwood and/or heartwood) of recently dead trees, but some attack stressed trees that are still alive, and a few species attack healthy trees.<ref name= Hulcr2017>Hulcr, J. and Stelinski, L.L., 2017. The ambrosia symbiosis: From evolutionary ecology to practical management. Annual Review of Entomology, 62, pp.285-303.</ref> Species differ in their preference for different parts of trees, different stages of deterioration, and in the shape of their tunnels (\"galleries\"). However, the majority of ambrosia beetles are not specialized to any taxonomic group of hosts, unlike most [[phytophagous]] organisms including the closely related [[bark beetle]]s.\nOne species of ambrosia beetle, ''[[Austroplatypus incompertus]]'' exhibits [[eusociality]], one of the few organisms outside of [[Hymenoptera]] and [[Isoptera]] to do so.\n\n==Classification and diversity==\n[[Image:Xylosandrus crassiusculus galleryR.jpg|thumb|left|Gallery of ''[[Xylosandrus crassiusculus]]'' split open, with pupae and black fungus]]\n\nUntil recently ambrosia beetles have been placed in independent families Scolytidae and Platypodidae, however, they are in fact some of the most highly derived [[weevils]], and are now placed in the subfamilies [[Scolytinae]] and [[Platypodinae]] of Family [[Curculionidae]]<ref>Kuschel, G., R. A. B. Leschen, et al. (2000): Platypodidae under scrutiny. Invertebrate Taxonomy 14: 771-805.<br />Marvaldi, A. E., A. S. Sequeira, et al. (2002): Molecular and Morphological Phylogenetics of Weevils (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea): Do Niche Shifts Accompany Diversifcation? Systematic Biology 51(5): 761-785.<br/>Duane D. McKenna, Andrea S. Sequeira, Adriana E. Marvaldi, and Brian D. Farrell. 2009. Temporal lags and overlap in the diversification of weevil and flowering plant. PNAS 106:7083-7088.</ref> There are about 3,000 known beetle species employing the ambrosia strategy.<ref>Hulcr, J., Atkinson, T.H., Cognato, A.I., Jordal, B.H. and McKenna, D.D., 2015. Morphology, taxonomy, and phylogenetics of bark beetles. Bark beetles: biology and ecology of native and invasive species, pp.41-84.</ref>\n\nAmbrosia beetles are an [[Guild (ecology)|ecological guild]], but not a [[Clade|phylogenetic clade]]. The ambrosia habit is an example of [[convergent evolution]], as several groups evolved the same symbiotic relationship independently.<ref>Farrell, B. D., A. S. O. Sequeira, et al. (2001): The evolution of agriculture in beetles (Curculionidae: Scolytinae and Platypodinae). Evolution 55: 2011-2027.</ref> The highest diversity of ambrosia beetles is in the tropics. In the [[Paleotropical]] region, hundreds of species of [[Xyleborini]] and [[Platypodinae]] are the main agent initiating dead wood decomposition. In the [[Neotropic]]s, [[Platypodinae]] and [[Xyleborini]] are joined by the scolytine tribe [[Cortylini]]. Compared to the diversity in the tropics, ambrosia beetle fauna in the temperate zone is rather limited. In the [[Nearctic]] region it is dominated by a few species from Cortylini, Xyleborini and [[Xyloterini]]. In the [[Palearctic]] [[ecozone]], significant groups are Xyloterini and Xyleborini, joined by [[Scolytoplatypodini]] in the Far East.\n\n[[Image:Dinoplatypus chevrolati.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Dinoplatypus chevrolati]]'' from Papua New Guinea, an example of Platypodinae, another species-rich group of ambrosia beetles]]\n\n==The symbiotic relationship==\nBeetles and their [[larva]]e graze on [[mycelium]] exposed on the gallery walls and on bodies called [[sporodochia]], clusters of the fungus' spores. Most ambrosia beetle species don't ingest the wood tissue; instead, the sawdust resulting from the excavation is pushed out of the gallery. Following the larval and pupal stage, adult ambrosia beetles collect masses of fungal spores into their [[mycangium|mycangia]] and leave the gallery to find their own tree.\n\nA few dozen species of ambrosia fungi have been described, currently in the genera ''[[Ambrosiella]]'', ''[[Meredithiella]]'', and ''[[Phialophoropsis]]'' (from [[Microascales]]), ''[[Afroraffaelea]]'' and ''[[Raffaelea]]'' (from Ophiostomatales), ''[[Ambrosiozyma]]'' ([[Saccharomycetales]]), ''[[Fusarium]]'' and ''[[Geosmithia]]'' (from [[Hypocreales]]),  and ''[[Flavodon]]'' (from [[Basidiomycota]]).<ref name= Hulcr2017 /> Many more species remain to be discovered. Little is known about the [[bionomy]] or specificity of ambrosia fungi. Ambrosia fungi are thought to be dependent on transport and inoculation provided by their beetle symbionts, as they have not been found in any other [[habitat]]. All ambrosia fungi are probably [[asexual reproduction|asexual]] and clonal.<ref>Malloch, D., and M. Blackwell. 1993. Dispersal biology of ophiostomatoid fungi. p. 195-206. In: Ceratocystis and Ophiostoma: Taxonomy, Ecology and Pathology. Eds., Wingfield, M.J., K.A. Seifert, and J.F. Webber. APS, St. Paul.</ref> Some beetles are known to acquire (\"steal\") fungal [[pathogen|inoculum]] from fungal gardens of other ambrosia beetle species.<ref>Hulcr, J., Cognato, A. I. 2010. Repeated evolution of theft in fungus farming ambrosia beetles. Evolution, 64 (11): 3205-3212</ref>\n\n==Evolutionary origin==\nDuring their evolution, most scolytid and platypodid weevils became progressively more or less dependent on fungi regularly co-habiting dead trees. This evolution had various outcomes in different groups:\n* Some [[phloem]]-eating bark beetles (phloeophages) are vectors of [[phytopathogen]]ic fungi, which in some cases contribute to tree death.<ref>Paine, T. D., K. F. Raffa, et al. (1997): Interactions between scolytid bark beetles, their associated fungi and live host [[conifer]]s. Annual Review of Entomology 42: 179-206.</ref> The extent to which fungal pathogenicity benefits the beetles themselves is not at all trivial and remains disputed.<ref>Six, D.L. and Wingfield, M.J., 2011. The role of phytopathogenicity in bark beetle\u2013fungus symbioses: a challenge to the classic paradigm. Annual Review of Entomology, 56, pp.255-272.</ref>\n* Many of phloem-feeding bark beetles use phloem-infesting fungi as an addition to their diet. Some phloeophages became dependent on such a mixed diet and evolved [[mycangium|mycangia]] to transport their symbionts from maternal trees to newly infested trees.<ref>Klepzik, K. D. and D. L. Six (2004): Bark Beetle&nbsp;\u2013 Fungal Symbiosis: Context Dependency in Complex Associations. Symbiosis 37: 189-205.</ref> These beetles are called ''mycophloeophages''.\n* Ambrosia beetles and ambrosia fungi are thus only one end of the spectrum of the [[symbiosis|weevil-fungus association]], where both the beetle and the fungus became completely dependent on each other.<ref>Beaver, R. A. (1989): Insect-Fungus Relationship in the Bark and Ambrosia Beetles. Insect-Fungus Interactions. N. Wilding, N. M. Collins, P. M. Hammond and J. F. Webber, Academic Press: 121-143.</ref>\n\n==Impact on forests==\n\nThe vast majority of ambrosia beetles colonize dead trees, and have minor or no economic effect. A few species are able to colonize living stressed trees (Xylosandrus).<ref>Ranger, C.M., Reding, M.E., Persad, A.B. and Herms, D.A., 2010. Ability of stress\u2010related volatiles to attract and induce attacks by Xylosandrus germanus and other ambrosia beetles. Agricultural and Forest Entomology, 12(2), pp.177-185.</ref> A few species are able to attack live and healthy trees, and those can reach epidemic proportions in non-native, invaded regions (''Xyleborus glabratus'', ''Euwallacea fornicatus''<ref>Hulcr, J., Black, A., Prior, K., Chen, C.Y. and Li, H.F., 2017. Studies of ambrosia beetles (Coleoptera: Curculionidae) in their native ranges help predict invasion impact. Florida Entomologist, 100(2), pp.257-261.</ref>).\n\nBeetle species that readily colonize lumber, such as sawlogs, green lumber, and stave-bolts, often cause region-specific economic loss from the pinhole and stained-wood defects caused by their brood galleries. In Northern USA and Canada, conifer logs are attractive to ''Trypodendron lineatum'' (Oliv.) during the spring swarming flight (Dyer 1967).<ref name=\"dye\">Dyer, E.D.A. 1967. Relation of attack by ambrosia beetle (''Trypodendron lineatum'' (Oliv.)) to felling date of spruce in central British Columbia. For. Can., Can. For. Serv., Ottawa ON, Bi-mo. Res. Notes 23(2):11.</ref> Previous studies showed that short log sections become attractive more rapidly than corresponding long logs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Laurel wilt disease]]\n* [[Forest pathology]]\n* ''[[Euwallacea fornicatus]]''\n* ''[[Xyleborus glabratus]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikispecies|Platypodinae}}\n* [http://www.ambrosiasymbiosis.org Images and information] on the Ambrosia Symbiosis at the University of Florida.\n* The [https://web.archive.org/web/20130701003854/http://www.scolytid.msu.edu/ MSU HISL database] contains a worldwide species list of Xyleborini, a major group of ambrosia beetles, from the Catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae of S.L. Wood and D.E. Bright (1992)\n* A USDA-sponsored [http://itp.lucidcentral.org/id/wbb/xyleborini/ information resource and key] to the world genera of Xyleborini\n* [http://www.barkbeetles.info American Bark and Ambrosia Beetles]\n* More information on ambrosia beetle social behaviour and fungiculture on [http://behav.zoology.unibe.ch/index.php?pp=55&p=46]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120422080021/http://www.dontmovefirewood.org/blog/farewell-taco-topping.html Farewell to taco topping?] The effects of the Redbay ambrosia beetle and laurel wilt disease\n* Ambrosia beetles on the [[University of Florida|UF]] / [[Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences|IFAS]] Featured Creatures Web site\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/beetles/platypus.htm ''Platypus'' spp., ambrosia beetles]\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/asian_ambrosia_beetle.htm ''Xylosandrus crassiusculus'', Asian (or granulate) ambrosia beetle]\n** [http://entomology.ifas.ufl.edu/creatures/trees/black_twig_borer.htm ''Xylosandrus compactus'', black twig borer]\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* van de Peppel, L. J. J., Aanen, D. K., & Biedermann, P. H. W. (2018). ''[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1754504817301848 Low intraspecific genetic diversity indicates asexuality and vertical transmission in the fungal cultivars of ambrosia beetles]''. Fungal Ecology, 32, 57\u201364.\n\n[[Category:Woodboring beetles]]\n[[Category:Platypodinae]]\n[[Category:Scolytinae]]\n", "name_user": "2601:648:8380:a960:d01f:963e:9fc8:79b8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambrosia_beetle"}
{"title_page": "Sunshine Suites", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Sunshine Suites\n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Public company|Private]]\n| foundation       = [[New York City]], [[United States|U.S.]] ({{Start date|2001}})\n| founder          = Cheni Yerushalmi<br />Joseph Raby\n| location_city    = [[New York City]], [[New York (U.S. state)|New York]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = 3 locations at 2010-11-03<br />[[Tribeca]]<br />[[NoHo]]<br />[[Bronx]]\n| area_served      = [[North America]]\n| key_people       = Cheni Yerushalmi <small>([[Entrepreneur|Managing Partner]])</small> <br />\n                             Joseph Raby  <small>([[Entrepreneur|Managing Partner]])</small>\n| industry         = [[Business Incubator]]\n| products         = [[Shared office space]]s, [[virtual office space]]s\n| services         = \n| revenue          = US$4.0 million (2009) {{increase}} 318.6% from 2005\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = Cheni Yerushalmi<br />Joseph Raby\n| num_employees    = 20 (2009)\n| parent           = Sunshine Realty Management\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\n| homepage         = {{URL|sunshineny.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Sunshine Suites''' was a [[business incubator]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/bronx/2010/11/04/2010-11-04_city_breaks_ground_on_first_business_incubator_in_the_bx.html |title=City breaks ground on first business incubator in the Bronx's Hunts Point |accessdate=2010-11-04 |last=Jaccarino |first=Mike |date=2010-11-04 |work=New York Daily News}}</ref> It was founded in 2001 and  managed by [[Sunshine Realty Management]].<ref name=\"Sunshine Realty Management\">{{cite web |url=http://www.inc.com/inc5000/2009/company-profile.html?id=200909590\n |title=Inc. Magazine company profile #959 |accessdate=2009 |work=Inc. Magazine}}</ref><ref name=\"Managing Partners\">{{cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9500E2D61030F935A15751C1A9629C8B63 |title=SQUARE FEET/Manhattan; Working Alone, Together |accessdate=2010-11-04 |last=Bahney |first=Anna |date=2004-12-26 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> In September 2010, [[Wall Street Journal]]<ref name=\"Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/09/30/seven-places-to-start-a-tech-company-in-new-york-city/ |title=Seven Places To Start A Tech Company In New York City |accessdate=2010-09-30 |last=Hotz |first=Alexander |date=2010-09-30 |work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> included Sunshine Suites in a list of locations tech entrepreneurs should consider if they\u2019re hunting for office space in New York City.  {{As of|2017|January|df=}}, it had closed its doors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119111838/http://sunshineny.com/|title=Sunshine Suites (archive.com snapshot)|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2010, [[New York City]] broke ground on its sixth business incubator and the first<ref name=\"Mayor Bloomberg\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/portal/site/nycgov/menuitem.c0935b9a57bb4ef3daf2f1c701c789a0/index.jsp?pageID=mayor_press_release&catID=1194&doc_name=http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/html/2010b/pr453-10.html&cc=unused1978&rc=1194&ndi=1 |title=Mayor Bloomberg announces first Bronx business incubator to support 400 entrepreneurs |accessdate=2010-11-03 |date=2010-11-03 |work=NYC.gov}}</ref> in the [[Bronx]] called the Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator.<ref name=\"Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\" />  This is a [[joint venture]] between the [[New York City Economic Development Corporation]] and Sunshine Suites, and located in the Hunt's Point [[American Bank Note Company Printing Plant|Banknote Building]].\n\nThe [[smartpitch.org|2012 SmartPitch Challenge]] is a business pitch competition borne out of the partnership between Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator, NYCEDC, CUNY Institute for Virtual Enterprise, Baruch's Lawnrence N Field Center for Entrepreneurship, and IBM.  The competition was announced at the Sunshine Bronx ribbon-cutting ceremony by [[Michael Bloomberg|Mayor Michael Bloomberg]] and commences February 3, 2012 with a kick-off event featuring Justin Cohen from [http://dc10.summitseries.com/ Summit Series].  The winners of this inaugural competition will receive mentorship from IBM entrepreneurial experts, office space at the Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator, admission to Entrepreneurial Boot Camp in Vermont during the summer of 2012, and an official launch for their business plans in Fall 2012.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sunshineny.com Official Sunshine Suites Website]\n* [http://smartpitch.org smartpitch.org]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of business incubators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{US Business Incubators}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Business incubators of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 2017]]\n\n\n{{US-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Sunshine Suites\n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Public company|Private]]\n| foundation       = [[New York City]], [[United States|U.S.]] ({{Start date|2001}})\n| founder          = Cheni Yerushalmi<br />Joseph Raby\n| location_city    = [[New York City]], [[New York (U.S. state)|New York]]\n| location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = 3 locations at 2010-11-03<br />[[Tribeca]]<br />[[NoHo]]<br />[[Bronx]]\n| area_served      = [[North America]]\n| key_people       = Cheni Yerushalmi <small>([[Entrepreneur|Managing Partner]])</small> <br />\n                             Joseph Raby  <small>([[Entrepreneur|Managing Partner]])</small>\n| industry         = [[Business Incubator]]\n| products         = [[Shared office space]]s, [[virtual office space]]s\n| services         = \n| revenue          = US$4.0 million (2009) {{increase}} 318.6% from 2005\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = Cheni Yerushalmi<br />Joseph Raby\n| num_employees    = 20 (2009)\n| parent           = Sunshine Realty Management\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\n| homepage         = {{URL|sunshineny.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Sunshine Suites''' was a [[business incubator]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/bronx/2010/11/04/2010-11-04_city_breaks_ground_on_first_business_incubator_in_the_bx.html |title=City breaks ground on first business incubator in the Bronx's Hunts Point |accessdate=2010-11-04 |last=Jaccarino |first=Mike |date=2010-11-04 |work=New York Daily News}}</ref> It was founded in 2001 and  managed by [[Sunshine Realty Management]].<ref name=\"Sunshine Realty Management\">{{cite web |url=http://www.inc.com/inc5000/2009/company-profile.html?id=200909590\n |title=Inc. Magazine company profile #959 |accessdate=2009 |work=Inc. Magazine}}</ref><ref name=\"Managing Partners\">{{cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9500E2D61030F935A15751C1A9629C8B63 |title=SQUARE FEET/Manhattan; Working Alone, Together |accessdate=2010-11-04 |last=Bahney |first=Anna |date=2004-12-26 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> In September 2010, [[Wall Street Journal]]<ref name=\"Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2010/09/30/seven-places-to-start-a-tech-company-in-new-york-city/ |title=Seven Places To Start A Tech Company In New York City |accessdate=2010-09-30 |last=Hotz |first=Alexander |date=2010-09-30 |work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> included Sunshine Suites in a list of locations tech entrepreneurs should consider if they\u2019re hunting for office space in New York City.  {{As of|2017|January|df=}}, it had closed it's doors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119111838/http://sunshineny.com/|title=Sunshine Suites (archive.com snapshot)|last=|first=|date=January 19, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2010, [[New York City]] broke ground on its sixth business incubator and the first<ref name=\"Mayor Bloomberg\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc.gov/portal/site/nycgov/menuitem.c0935b9a57bb4ef3daf2f1c701c789a0/index.jsp?pageID=mayor_press_release&catID=1194&doc_name=http://www.nyc.gov/html/om/html/2010b/pr453-10.html&cc=unused1978&rc=1194&ndi=1 |title=Mayor Bloomberg announces first Bronx business incubator to support 400 entrepreneurs |accessdate=2010-11-03 |date=2010-11-03 |work=NYC.gov}}</ref> in the [[Bronx]] called the Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator.<ref name=\"Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator\" />  This is a [[joint venture]] between the [[New York City Economic Development Corporation]] and Sunshine Suites, and located in the Hunt's Point [[American Bank Note Company Printing Plant|Banknote Building]].\n\nThe [[smartpitch.org|2012 SmartPitch Challenge]] is a business pitch competition borne out of the partnership between Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator, NYCEDC, CUNY Institute for Virtual Enterprise, Baruch's Lawnrence N Field Center for Entrepreneurship, and IBM.  The competition was announced at the Sunshine Bronx ribbon-cutting ceremony by [[Michael Bloomberg|Mayor Michael Bloomberg]] and commences February 3, 2012 with a kick-off event featuring Justin Cohen from [http://dc10.summitseries.com/ Summit Series].  The winners of this inaugural competition will receive mentorship from IBM entrepreneurial experts, office space at the Sunshine Bronx Business Incubator, admission to Entrepreneurial Boot Camp in Vermont during the summer of 2012, and an official launch for their business plans in Fall 2012.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sunshineny.com Official Sunshine Suites Website]\n* [http://smartpitch.org smartpitch.org]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of business incubators]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{US Business Incubators}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Business incubators of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 2017]]\n\n\n{{US-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "it's \u2192 its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunshine_Suites"}
{"title_page": "Monica Rial", "text_new": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = Monica Rial isn't real. She is a figment of your imagination and figments of our imaginations don't deserve wikipedia pages dammit!{{April Fools}}\n  |timestamp = 20200401200207\n  |help = \n}}\n{{short description|American voice actress}}\n{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Monica Rial\n| image              = Monica Rial GalaxyCon Richmond 2020.jpg\n| caption            = Rial at GalaxyCon Richmond in 2020\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1975|10|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.<!-- birthplace confirmed by connected contributor Hellomonichan -->\n| residence          = [[Dallas]], Texas, U.S.<ref name=\"observer\"/><br />Houston, Texas, U.S.<!-- listed on her Twitter account as of November 3, 2015-->\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Houston]]<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n| occupation         = Voice actress, ADR director, script writer\n| years_active       = 1999\u2013present\n| agent              = Mary Collins Agency\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = Natalie Rial (sister)<ref name=\"natalie\">{{Cite tweet|number=396448214280196096 |title=Yes, you read the Girls Und Panzer cast list correctly. Natalie Rial is my little sister. The Rials are taking over the anime world. \ud83d\ude1c | user=rialisms | author=Monica Rial | date=November 1, 2013 | access-date=2017-05-26 }}</ref><br>Miguel Rial (brother)\n| birthname          = Monica Jean Rial\n| alias              = <!-- NEED SOURCE Dorothy Garrett, Lisa Blanchard -->\n| url                = {{URL|themonicarial.com}}\n}}\n'''Monica Jean Rial''' (born October 5, 1975)<ref>{{cite tweet | title=It's my birthday Monday! All I want is for you to watch #MichikoAndHatchin tonight!!!! | date=October 3, 2015 | user=Rialisms | author=Monica Rial | number=650544004615012352 | accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref><!-- year confirmed by connected contributor Hellomonichan -->  is an American voice actress, [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|ADR director]] and [[screenwriter|script writer]] affiliated with [[Funimation]] and [[Seraphim Digital]]/[[Sentai Filmworks]]. She provides voices for English language versions of Japanese [[anime]] films and television series.\n\n==Early life==\nMonica Jean Rial was born on October 5, 1975 in [[Houston, Texas]]. Her father is from [[Pontevedra]], Galicia, Spain. When she was young, her family would often visit Spain. She would translate for her younger brother some of the European Spanish-dubbed cartoons which included anime shows ''[[Doraemon]]'' and ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', often imitating the various characters.<ref name=\"latino\"/><ref name=\"observer\"/> Rial studied ballet, tap, and jazz, but transitioned to musical theater when was 12.<ref name=\"otakunews 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.otakunews.com/article.php?story=952|title=Otaku News : Interview with Monica Rial and Chris Patton|first=Rebecca |last=McCarthy|date=September 21, 2006|work=Otaku News|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> She studied acting through high school as well as college at the [[University of Houston]].<ref name=\"resume\"/><ref name=\"observer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/arts/the-fun-factory-inside-funimation-the-anime-dubbing-powerhouse-thats-keeping-dallas-actors-in-work-8095737|title=The Fun Factory: Inside Funimation, the Anime-Dubbing Powerhouse That's Keeping Dallas Actors in Work|first=Caroline|last=North|date=March 8, 2016|work=[[The Dallas Observer]]|accessdate=July 18, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with Otaku News, Rial mentioned voice actor inspirations from ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[Family Guy]]'' and ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]''.<ref name=\"otakunews 2006\"/> She was working on a theater show with [[Jason Douglas]], who suggested she audition for [[ADV Films]].\n\n==Career==\nRial's first voice-over role was some [[walla]] in the 1999 dub of ''[[Martian Successor Nadesico]]''. In an interview with Otaku News, Rial said she had to talk for two minutes straight as folks in a crowd telling the Jovians to go home.<ref name=\"otakunews 2006\"/> She would later land main character roles as Miharu in ''[[Gasaraki]]'', Natsume in ''[[Generator Gawl]]'', and the title character in ADV Films' production of ''[[Hello Kitty (TV series)|Hello Kitty's Animation Theater]]'',<ref name=\"diehard\"/><ref name=\"otakunews\"/> the last of which was one of ADV's best-selling DVDs.<ref name=\"activeanime 2006\"/> In 2001, she voiced Izumi in the baseball anime ''[[Princess Nine]]'' and in 2002, she got to voice Hyatt in ''[[Excel Saga]]'', which she listed among her absolute favorites.<ref name=\"diehard\"/>\n\nIn 2003, Rial voiced best-friend character [[List of Full Metal Panic characters#Kyoko Tokiwa|Kyoko Tokiwa]] in ''[[Full Metal Panic!]]'', and got to reprise her for ''Full Metal Panic? Fumoffu'' and ''Full Metal Panic: The Second Raid''. In the same year, Rial voiced Kirika Yumura, the quiet assassin partner in ''[[Noir (anime)|Noir]]''. Rial said that Kirika was challenging because she had very few words but had to convey a lot of emotions.<ref name=\"diehard\"/> She also noted that Kirika's personality changed over the course of the series, so she voiced her to be more emotional in later episodes which drew some criticism from fans. She also voiced Lila in ''[[Najica Blitz Tactics]]'' where she also got to do a DVD commentary along with fellow actress [[Kira Vincent-Davis]]. The commentaries have become popular as she receives feedback from fans about them at anime conventions.<ref name=\"otakunews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.otakunews.com/us/article.php?story=68|title=Otaku News : An Interview With Monica Rial|first=Rebecca|last=McCarthy|date=September 8, 2004|work=Otaku News|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> She voiced female protagonist [[List of RahXephon characters#Haruka Shitou|Haruka Shitou]] in the sci-fi show ''[[RahXephon]]''.\n\nIn 2004, Rial started voice-over work with the anime dubbing company [[Funimation]] in the Dallas/Ft. Worth area. During that year, she voiced [[List of Case Closed characters#Amy Yoshida|Amy]] in the long-running detective anime series ''[[Case Closed (manga)|Case Closed]]'', and [[List of Fullmetal Alchemist characters#Lyra|Lyra]] (aka Dante) in the drama series ''[[Fullmetal Alchemist]]''. Both of these shows were featured on Cartoon Network. She also voiced co-lead character Lumiere in ''[[Kiddy Grade]]''.<ref name=\"ann 20040911\"/> Meanwhile, with ADV, she voiced [[List of Azumanga Daioh characters#Nyamo|Nyamo-sensei]] in the school comedy ''[[Azumanga Daioh]]''. She had also taken over some character roles as Momiji in ''[[Blue Seed]]'' and Maya in ''[[Neon Genesis Evangelion]]''. Rial said that it was very difficult to try to sound like the previous voice actors, especially Maya's low voice, so she tried her own approach. She also got to voice Pen-Pen the penguin in ''Evangelion''.<ref name=\"ann 20040513\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2004-05-13/2|title=Interview: Colleen Clinkenbeard and Monica Rial|first=Chris|last=Fey|date=May 13, 2004|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 11, 2015}}</ref> In 2005, she voiced the serious lead character Jo in a team of mercenary girls in the cyberpunk science fiction series ''[[Burst Angel]]''.<ref name=\"burst angel review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/30653/burst-angel-deaths-angel-v1/|title=Burst Angel \u2013 Death's Angel v.1|first=Don|last=Houston|date=September 24, 2007|work=DVD Talk|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRial continued to land leading roles in anime shows. In 2006, she voiced the title character in ''[[Nanaka 6/17]]'', about a 17-year-old girl who, through an accident, has amnesia and regresses to her 6-year-old self. In ''[[Speed Grapher]]'' she voiced female protagonist [[List of Speed Grapher characters#Kagura Tenn\u014dzu|Kagura Tenn\u014dzu]], and in the ADV Films remake of ''[[The Super Dimension Fortress Macross|Macross]]'', she voiced [[Misa Hayase]].<ref name=\"activeanime 2006\"/> In 2007, she voiced [[Sakura (Tsubasa: Reservoir Chronicle)|Sakura]] in the English anime adaptation of Clamp's ''[[Tsubasa: Reservoir Chronicle]]''; Maria in ''[[Witchblade (anime)|Witchblade]]'';<ref name=\"marchi 20131010\"/> Misuzu Kamio, a heroine in ''[[Air (TV series)|Air]]'', and the title character in ''[[Kurau: Phantom Memory]]''.  She also voiced lead characters Misao Shinohara, Sasami's best friend in ''[[Sasami: Magical Girls Club]]''; and heroine [[Asa Shigure]] in the harem comedy ''[[Shuffle!]]''.\n\n[[File:2017 Wizard World Columbus - Monica Rial (36039256730).jpg|thumb|Rial at Wizard World Columbus in 2017]]\n\nIn 2010, when ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' was remade as ''Dragon Ball Z Kai'', Rial got to voice the heroine character [[Bulma]]. She voiced other lead girl characters such as Miya Asami in ''[[Sekirei]]'', [[Tsubaki Nakatsukasa]] in ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'', May Chang in ''[[Fullmetal Alchemist Brotherhood]]'', and Ringo in ''[[Casshern Sins]]''. Both ''Soul Eater'' and ''Fullmetal Alchemist Brotherhood'' have had sizeable runs on [[Adult Swim]]'s [[Toonami]] block. In 2011, she voiced the title character Mina Tepes in ''[[Dance in the Vampire Bund]]'', as well as several lead female characters in ensemble shows ''[[Rosario + Vampire]]'', ''[[Highschool of the Dead]]'' and ''[[Fairy Tail]]'', such as Yukari Sendou, [[Shizuka Marikawa]], and Mirajane Strauss respectively.\n\nRial voiced more leads in 2012 with [[List of Deadman Wonderland characters#Shiro|Shiro]] in ''[[Deadman Wonderland]]'' which also broadcast on [[Adult Swim]], Stocking in the raunchy comedy ''[[Panty & Stocking with Garterbelt]]''. In 2013, she voiced the heroine character Haruko Amaya in the harem comedy ''[[Maken-ki!]]'' and Iori Nagase in the school anime series ''[[Kokoro Connect]]''. With regards to her lead role of Michiko Malandro in ''[[Michiko & Hatchin]]'', which was released on DVD in 2013 and was broadcast on [[Adult Swim]] in 2015, Rial said that out of the 300 or so characters she had voiced, only two of them were Hispanic, and she liked that her character wasn't a stereotype.<ref name=\"latino\"/> In 2014 and 2015, she voiced the title characters in the comedies ''[[Watamote]]'' and ''[[Maid Sama!]]'' as Tomoko Kuroki and Misaki Ayuzawa, respectively. <!-- more can be written about her recent works -->\n\nIn addition to voice acting, Rial has been steadily involved in ADR script writing, with work in the English dubs for ''[[D.N. Angel]]'', ''[[Madlax]]'', and ''[[Gatchaman]]''. In an interview with Active Anime, Rial said she would \"take the direct translation and write it into a coherent scene that matches the lip flaps\".<ref name=\"activeanime 2006\">{{cite web|url=http://activeanime.com/html/2006/01/09/monica-rial/|title=\u00bb MONICA RIAL|author=|date=January 9, 2006|work=ActiveAnime|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> At later anime conventions, Rial has mentioned that ADR script writing has kept her quite occupied, especially with [[Funimation#Simuldub program|simuldubs]], which are shows that are locally dubbed soon after the original broadcast. She has also written columns for ''[[Newtype]]''{{'}}s USA edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/33522|title=AICN Anime \u2013 A Survey of Print Resources|last=Green|first=Scott|date=August 1, 2007|work=Aint It Cool News|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> In January 2018, Rial has announced that she is taking time off of script adaptation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Rialisms/status/950510647514730496|title=Just to clarify, when I said I was taking some time off I meant from script adapting. I\u2019m still voice acting! That\u2019s my passion!|last=Rial|first=Monica|date=2018-01-08|website=@Rialisms|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Rial alleged that she had been sexually assaulted by fellow voice actor [[Vic Mignogna]] in 2007.<ref name=\"ann 2019-02-20\">{{cite news|author=Rafael Antonio Pineda|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2019-02-20/bulma-voice-actress-monica-rial-shares-alleged-inappropriate-encounters-with-vic-mignogna/.143664|title=Bulma Voice Actress Monica Rial Shares Alleged Inappropriate Encounters With Vic Mignogna|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2019-02-20|accessdate=2019-02-20}}</ref> On April 19, 2019, Mignogna filed a lawsuit against Rial, her fianc\u00e9, Ron Toye, as well as Funimation and [[Jamie Marchi]] for tortious interference, civil conspiracy, and defamation in regards to Rial's allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-04-19/vic-mignogna-sues-funimation-jamie-marchi-monica-rial-ronald-toye/.145898|title=Vic Mignogna Sues Funimation, Jamie Marchi, Monica Rial, Ronald Toye|website=Anime News Network|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> On July 19, 2019, Rial, Toye and Marchi all filed [[Strategic lawsuit against public participation|anti-SLAPP]] motions for Mignogna to dismiss his lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-22/monica-rial-ronald-toye-jamie-marchi-also-file-motions-to-dismiss-vic-mignogna-lawsuit/.149217|title=Monica Rial, Ronald Toye, Jamie Marchi Also File Motions to Dismiss Vic Mignogna's Lawsuit|website=Anime News Network|language=en|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> On October 4, 2019, the case was dismissed, and all the charges against Funimation, Marchi, Rial and Toye were dropped.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mateo |first1=Alex |title=Vic Mignogna's Civil Case Against Funimation, Voice Actress Monica Rial, Ron Toye Dismissed |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-04/vic-mignogna-civil-case-against-funimation-voice-actress-monica-rial-ron-toye-dismissed/.151881 |website=Anime News Network |accessdate=October 5, 2019 |date=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRial has a younger brother, Miguel, and a younger sister, Natalie, who is also an actress. Both siblings have voiced in anime dubs.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=307503149629964289|title=In other news, it's my little bro Miguel Rial's bday! He was in FMA ep 27 as \"Boy with the broken train\"! Happy 29, Guels! #MylilBroRocks!|last=Rial|first=Monica|date=2013-03-01|user=Rialisms|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref><ref name=\"natalie\"/> Rial is currently engaged to Ron Toye.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1118589196367740931|user=Rialisms|first=Monica|last=Rial|date= April 17, 2019|title=@RonToye is my fianc\u00e9. Our life is pretty weird already. That said, I welcome more weirdness.}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Anime===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of voice performances and production work in anime\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Crew role, Notes <!-- place crew roles here -->\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Source<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1999}} || ''[[Martian Successor Nadesico]]'' || Mikako, Miss Kobayashi || Debut roles || <ref name=\"diehard\"/><ref name=\"otakunews 2006\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2000}} || ''[[Hello Kitty (TV series)|Hello Kitty's Animation Theater]]'' || Hello Kitty || ADV and Sanrio production || Press<ref name=\"activeanime 2006\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2000}} || ''[[Gasaraki]]'' || Miharu || || <ref name=\"diehard\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2000}} || ''[[Generator Gawl]]'' || [[Generator Gawl#Natsume|Natsume]] || <!-- ADV episode credits --> || <ref name=\"diehard\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2001}} || ''[[Princess Nine]]'' || [[Princess Nine#Izumi Himuro|Izumi Himuro]] || <!-- ADV episode credits --> || <ref name=\"diehard\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/princess-nine/dvd-complete-collection/.75038|title=Princess Nine DVD Complete Series|author=|date=|website=animenewsnetwork.com|accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><!-- Hilary Haag, Monica Rial, and a heap of other ADV old guard shine with enthu