ign Fitness<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mason360.gmu.edu/alignfitness/home/ |title=Home - Align Fitness {{!}} George Mason University|website=mason360.gmu.edu|access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|Sports Ministry Fellowship \n|-\n|Anointed Vessels of Unity\n|AVU\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Apostles Campus Church\n|ACC\n|Christianity\n|Anglican\n|\n|Church\n|-\n|Arise Campus Ministry\n|\n|Christianity\n|[[Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)]], \n[[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] ([[Anglicanism|Anglican]]), [[Presbyterian Church (USA)|Presbyterian (USA)]],\n\n[[United Church of Christ]],\n\n[[United Methodist Church|United Methodist]] ([[Wesleyan theology|Wesleyan]])\n|\n|[[Wesley Foundation]], \nCanterbury Club,\n\n[[Presbyterian House]]\n|-\n|Baha'i Club\n|\n|Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith\n|\n|Bah\u00e1\u2019\u00ed Campus Ministry \n|\n|-\n|Bridges International\n|\n|[[Christianity]]\n|\n|Bridges International\n|Community Organization \n|-\n|George Mason Catholic Campus Ministry \n(St. Robert Bellarmine Chapel)\n|CCM\n|Christianity\n|[[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n|Works with the Fellowship of Catholic University Students \n(FOCUS) | [[Catholic campus ministry]]\n|Fellowship & Church\n|-\n|GMU [[Chi Alpha (Christian Fellowship)|Chi Alpha]] \n(Chi Alpha Christian Fellowship)\n|\u03a7\u0391 (GMUXA)\n|Christianity\n|inter-denominational local chapters\n|Chi Alpha Campus Ministries \n([[Assemblies of God USA]]\u2014national affiliate)\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|GMU Christians on Campus\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|Christians on Campus\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Coptic Orthodox Christian Association\n|\n|Christianity\n|[[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Orthodox Christian Church]] \n|Coptic Orthodox Christian Association\n|Association\n|-\n|Cru (MasonCru)\n|Cru\n|Christianity\n|[[interdenominational]]\n|[[Cru (Christian organization)]]\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Delight Ministries\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|Delight Ministries\n|A College Women's Community Ministry\n|-\n|Disciples on Campus\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|Disciples on Campus\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|EPIC Movement (Asian American Fellowship)\n|EPIC\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Cultural, Fellowship\n|-\n|Every Nation Campus - GMU\n|ENC\n|Christianity\n|[[Evangelicalism]]\n|[[Every Nation Churches & Ministries]]\n|Campus Ministry & Church\n|-\n|Fellowship of Catholic University Students \n|FOCUS\n|Christianity\n|Catholic\n|[[Fellowship of Catholic University Students]]\n|Fellowship & Church\n|-\n|Fellowship of Christian Athletes\n|FCA\n|Christianity\n|interdenominational\nnon-denominational\n|[[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]]\n|Sports Ministry Fellowship\n|-\n|First Love Church\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Fellowship & Church\n|-\n|Hillel\n|\n|[[Judaism|Jewish (Religious Judaism)]]\n|\n|\n|Professional Association\n|-\n|Immanuel Christian Fellowship\n|ICF\n|Christianity\n|non-denominational (Evangelical-leaning)\n|Immanuel Bible Church\n(Servants Ministry)\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Klesis\n|\u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2\n|Christianity\n|[[Baptists|Baptist]]\n|\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Korean Bible Study of GMU\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Cultural,\nFellowship (conducted in Korean)\n|-\n|GMU [Make]New\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|MakeNew Christian Fellowship\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Mason InterVarsity\n|IV\n|Christianity\n|interdenominational (Evangelical-leaning)\n|[[InterVarsity Christian Fellowship]]\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Muslim Leadership Development\n|\n|Islam\n|\n|\n|Leadership Development\n|-\n|Muslim Students' Association\n|\n|Islam\n|all Muslims <br />\n|\n|Halaqas (study circles)\n|-\n|NxGeneration Campus Ministry\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Young Adult/Youth Ministry\n|-\n|Orthodox Christian Fellowship\n|\n|Christianity\n|Orthodox Christianity\n|\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Patriot Christian Ministry\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Promises United in God\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Fellowship\n|-\n|Ratio Christi\n|\n|Christianity\n|non-denominational \n|Ratio Christi\n|Apologetics\n|-\n|SERVE\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Community Services\n|-\n|Secular Student Alliance (GMU)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mason360.gmu.edu/ssagmu/home/ |title=Home - Secular Student Alliance {{!}} George Mason University|website=mason360.gmu.edu|access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n|SSA\n|[[Nontheism]]\n|human-based ethics\n|Secular Student Alliance\n|Special Interest\n|-\n|Sikh Student Association\n|\n|[[Sikhism]]\n|\n|\n|Association\n|-\n|Student Bible Study\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Bible Study\n|-\n|The Gathering\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Movement \n|-\n|The Impact Movement at Mason \n(Black, African, African-American Fellowship)\n|\n|Christianity\n|\n|\n|Cultural, Fellowship\n|-\n|The Latter-Day Saint Student Association\n|LDSSA\n|[[Mormonism]]\n|[[Latter Day Saint movement]]\n|[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\n|Gospel Study (Institute of Religion Class)\n|-\n|University Bible Fellowship\n|UBF\n|Christianity\n|[[Mainline Protestant|mainline evangelical]]\n|\n|Fellowship & Church\n|-\n|Young Life\n|YL\n|Christianity\n|[[Presbyterianism]]\n|[[Young Life]]\n|Fellowship\n|}\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{{Main|George Mason Patriots}}\n{{See also|George Mason Patriots men's basketball|2005\u201306 George Mason Patriots men's basketball team}}\n\n====Division I teams====\n[[File:GMU-BBallGame-Spring05.jpg|thumbnail|Hofstra visits the Patriot Center{{refn|now known as the [[EagleBank Arena]]}} on January 26, 2005]]\nThe [[George Mason Patriots]] are the athletic teams of George Mason University located in Fairfax, Virginia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://about.gmu.edu/campuses/ |title=Campuses |work=About Mason|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401222448/http://about.gmu.edu/campuses/|archive-date=April 1, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=March 16, 2015}}</ref> The Patriots compete in Division I of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] as members of the [[Atlantic 10]] Conference for most sports. About 485 student-athletes compete in 22 men's and women's Division I sports \u2013 baseball, basketball, cross-country, golf, lacrosse, rowing, soccer, softball, swimming and diving, tennis, indoor and outdoor track and field, volleyball, and wrestling. Intercollegiate men's and women's teams are members of the National Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I, the Atlantic 10, the Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC), the Eastern Intercollegiate Volleyball Association (EIVA), the Eastern Wrestling League (EWL), and the Intercollegiate Association of Amateur Athletes of America (IC4A).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://irr.gmu.edu/FastFacts/ |title=Mason Visitors Center \u2013 Mason Facts and Figures |work=gmu.edu |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211191347/http://irr.gmu.edu/FastFacts/ |archivedate=February 11, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Intramural Club Sports<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mason360.gmu.edu/club_signup?group_type=14121 |title=Listing of Groups and Organizations {{!}} Mason360|website=mason360.gmu.edu|access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref>====\nIn addition to its NCAA Division I teams, George Mason University has several club sports.<ref name=\"George Mason Club Sports\">{{cite web |url=https://recreation.gmu.edu/club-sports/ |title=Club Sports \u2013 Recreation \u2013 George Mason University |work=gmu.edu}}</ref> The club sports offer students a chance to compete at a high level without the time commitment of a D-I/Varsity team in sports including \u2013 badminton, baseball, basketball (women's), bowling, cricket, crew, cycling, equestrian, fencing, field hockey, football, ice hockey, lacrosse (men's and women's), paintball, powerlifting, quidditch, rugby (men's and women's), running, soccer (men's and women's), swimming, tae kwon do, trap & skeet, triathlon, ultimate frisbee (men's and women's), volleyball (men's and women's), wrestling, and underwater hockey. Clubs have a competitive range from regional competition to yearly participation in [[Collegiate club sports|U.S. National College Club Level Championships]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name \n!Sport\n|-\n|Badminton Club\n|Badminton \n|-\n|Club Baseball\n|Baseball\n|-\n|Club Field Hockey\n|Field Hockey\n|-\n|Club Football\n|Football\n|-\n|George Mason Club Softball\n|Softball\n|-\n|George Mason Crew Club\n|Crew\n|-\n|George Mason Fencing Club\n|Fencing\n|-\n|George Mason Men's Club Soccer\n|Soccer\n|-\n|George Mason Squash Club\n|Squash\n|-\n|George Mason University Running Club\n|Running\n|-\n|GMU Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu\n|Jiu-Jitsu (Brazilian)\n|-\n|GMU Club Tennis\n|Tennis\n|-\n|GMU Esports\n|Esports\n|-\n|GMU Men's Lacrosse Club\n|Lacrosse\n|-\n|GMU Men's Rugby Football Club\n|Rugby Football\n|-\n|GMU Trap and Skeet\n|Trap and Skeet\n|-\n|Log Rolling Club\n|Log Rolling\n|-\n|Mason Equestrian Club\n|Equestrian Sports\n|-\n|Mason Powerlifting\n|Powerlifting\n|-\n|Mason Quidditch Club\n|Quidditch\n|-\n|Mason Swim Club\n|Swimming \n|-\n|Mason Taekwondo\n|Taekwondo\n|-\n|Men's Club Ultimate\n|Ultimate Frisbee\n|-\n|Men's Club Volleyball\n|Volleyball\n|-\n|Men's Ice Hockey\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|Underwater Hockey\n|Underwater Hockey\n|-\n|Women's Club Basketball\n|Basketball\n|-\n|Women's Club Ice Hockey\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|Women's Club Lacrosse\n|Lacrosse\n|-\n|Women's Club Soccer\n|Soccer\n|-\n|Women's Rugby Club\n|Rugby\n|-\n|Women's Ultimate Frisbee\n|Ultimate Frisbee\n|-\n|Women's Volleyball Club\n|Volleyball\n|}\n\n====Performing Arts====\nMason Players\n\nThe Mason Players is a faculty lead student organization that produces six productions. This season includes two \"Main Stage\" productions, which are directed by faculty members or guest artists. As well as \"Studio\" productions, which are directed by students through an application process within Mason Players. There is also an annual production of \"Originals\", which consists of 10 minute original plays written by students. Full time students of George Mason University, both outside and a part of the School of Theater are allowed to audition for these productions.\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharp |first1=Rachel |url=https://theater.gmu.edu/student-opportunities/mason-players |title=Mason Players |website=Theater at GMU}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty and alumni==\n[[File:James Buchanan by Atlas network.jpg|thumb|100px|[[James M. Buchanan]], [[Nobel Memorial Prize]]-winning [[economist]] and namesake of James Buchanan Hall]]\n[[File:VernonSmith2.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Vernon L. Smith]], Nobel Memorial Prize-winning economist and namesake of Vernon Smith Hall]]\n[[File:Gordon tullock.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Gordon Tullock]], co-founder of [[public choice]] economics]]\n{{Main|List of George Mason University people}}\n\n===Faculty===\n* [[Donald J. Boudreaux]], economist, contributor of the ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review'' and the ''Cafe Hayek'' blog, and author of the books ''Globalization'' and ''Hypocrites and Half-Wits''\n* [[James M. Buchanan]], 1986 [[Nobel Memorial Prize]] winner for Economics<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schudel |first1=Matt |title=James Buchanan, GMU economist who won Nobel |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/james-buchanan-gmu-economist-who-won-nobel/2013/01/09/4557617e-5a86-11e2-beee-6e38f5215402_story.html |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Bryan Caplan]], economist, blogger at [[EconTalk]], author of [[The Myth of the Rational Voter]] and ''The Case Against Education''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/conversations/2018/2/16/16870408/public-education-libertarianism-democracy-bryan-caplan |title=Why this economist thinks public education is mostly pointless |publisher=Vox |date=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Tyler Cowen]], economist, director of the [[Mercatus Center]] at Mason and founder of the blog Marginal Revolution<ref>Cowen: {{Hanging indent | {{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/27/tyler-cowen-pepper-sprayed_n_5042358.html |title=Tyler Cowen Pepper Sprayed While Teaching Law School Class On Vigilantism |work=Huffington Post |date=March 27, 2014 |first=Arin |last=Greenwood}}}} {{Hanging indent | {{cite magazine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gregorymcneal/2014/03/27/law-professor-pepper-sprayed-during-class-by-man-demanding-a-citizens-arrest/ |title=Law Professor Pepper Sprayed During Class By Man Demanding A 'Citizen's Arrest' |magazine=Forbes |date=March 27, 2014 |first=Greg |last=McNeal}}}} {{Hanging indent | {{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/tyler-cowens-attacker-thought-the-professor-was-controlling-his-mind-cowen-testifies/2014/04/29/a4c5b9f4-cfb9-11e3-b812-0c92213941f4_story.html |first=Rachel |last=Weiner |title=Tyler Cowen's attacker thought the professor was controlling his mind, Cowen testifies |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=April 29, 2014}}}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher d'Amboise]], [[danseur]], [[choreographer]], [[Tony Award]] nominee.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/song-and-dance-stars-new-work-the-studio-gets-nyc-workshop-com-121632 | title=Song and Dance Star's New Work The Studio Gets NYC Workshop |magazine=Playbill |date=August 30, 2004}}</ref>\n* [[Helen C. Frederick]], artist and printmaker\n* [[Jack Goldstone]], sociologist and political scientist specializing in revolutions; nonresident senior fellow at the [[Brookings Institution]]; 2014&nbsp;winner&nbsp;of [[Guggenheim Award]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/jack-goldstone/ |title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} Jack Goldstone|website=www.gf.org|language=en-US|access-date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Hugh Heclo]], political scientist, [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim Fellow]], and Clarence J. Robinson Professor of Public Affairs\n* [[Jonathan Katz (computer scientist)|Jonathan Katz]], cryptographer and co-author of Introduction to Modern Cryptography\n*[[Brett Kavanaugh]], Supreme Court Justice<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/23/politics/brett-kavanaugh-george-mason-professor-summer-class/index.html |title=Supreme Court Justice Brett Kavanaugh to teach summer class in England for George Mason law |first=Veronica |last=Stracqualursi |website=CNN|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Steven Pearlstein]], [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner for economics in the [[Washington Post]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/08/business/media/08pulitzers.html |work=The New York Times |title=Washington Post Wins Six Pulitzers |first=Richard |last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Russ Roberts]], economist and host of [[EconTalk]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackman |first1=Tom |title=GMU professor helps create viral rap videos \u2014 about economics |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-state-of-nova/post/gmu-prof-helps-create-viral-rap-videos--about-economics/2011/05/11/AFruUquG_blog.html |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=May 12, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Roy Rosenzweig]], [[Fulbright scholar]],&nbsp;historian,&nbsp;founded Center for History and New Media<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/12/AR2007101202489.html |title=Digital Historian Roy A. Rosenzweig |work=Washington Post |date=October 13, 2007 |accessdate=October 8, 2014 |author=Bernstein, Adam}}</ref>\n* [[Louise Shelley]], 2015 Andrew Carnegie Fellow from the [[Carnegie Corporation]] of New York.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Larkworthy |first1=Tyler |title=These are the Penn students fighting human trafficking |url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2017/03/students-against-human-trafficking-penn |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |newspaper=Daily Pennsylvanian |date=March 19, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Martin Sherwin]], [[Pulitzer Prize]]&nbsp;winner for his biography of [[Robert Oppenheimer]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Olson |first1=Wyatt |title=A-bomb Ended World War Ii, but Set Stage for the Cold War |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/a-bomb-ended-world-war-ii-but-set-stage-for-the-cold-war-1.365555 |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |newspaper=Stars and Stripes |date=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Vernon L. Smith]], 2002 [[Nobel Memorial Prize]]-winning economist.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gillespie |first1=Nick |last2=Lynch |first2=Michael W. |title=The Experimental Economist |issue=October |publisher=Reason |date=2002}}</ref>\n* [[Gordon Tullock]], co-founder of public choice economics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Somin |first1=Ilya |title=Gordon Tullock, RIP |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2014/11/05/gordon-tullock-rip/ |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |newspaper=Washington Post |date=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Roger Wilkins]], Clarence J. Robinson Professor of History and American Culture, [[Pulitzer Prize]] winner, journalist, civil rights leader and former Assistant Attorney General of the Unites States\n* [[Walter E. Williams]], John M. Olin Distinguished Professor of Economics<ref>{{cite news |last1=Irvine |first1=Spencer |title=Walter E. Williams Wins Bradley Prize for Work on Free Markets |url=https://www.academia.org/walter-e-williams-wins-bradley-prize-for-work-on-free-markets/ |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |publisher=Accuracy In Academia |date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alumni===\n* [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]], President of [[Puntland]] and Prime Minister of [[Somalia]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Gettleman |first=Jeffrey |title=Somalia Names New Prime Minister |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/24/world/africa/24somalia.html |accessdate=June 23, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626195247/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/24/world/africa/24somalia.html |archivedate=June 26, 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[Anousheh Ansari]], Iranian-American engineer, co-founder of Prodea Systems and the first Muslim woman in space<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Freed |first1=Benjamin |title=DC-Area Universities Warn Some Staff and Students Against Travel Outside US |url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/01/29/gwu-uva-umd-trump-travel-ban/ |accessdate=April 16, 2017 |magazine=Washingtonian |date=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[:de:Elsa Jean|Elsa Jean]], prominent American actress in the German \u201cadult film\u201d industry<ref name=\"AVN\">{{cite magazine|title=Elsa Jean|magazine=[[Adult Video News]]|url=http://www.avn.com/porn-stars/Elsa-Jean-604724.html|access-date=2016-04-24|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Justin Bour]], professional baseball player with the Los Angeles Angels of Aneheim <ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/nationals-journal/wp/2015/05/05/former-all-met-and-george-mason-patriot-justin-bour-homers-against-hometown-team/ |title=Former All-Met and George Mason Patriot Justin Bour homers against hometown team |last=Janes |first=Chelsea |date=May 5, 2015 |newspaper=The Washington Post |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286|access-date=March 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Anna E. Cabral]], [[Treasurer of the United States]] under President [[George W. Bush]]<ref>Patterson, R. B., & Zhang, H. Y. (n.d.). Right on the Money: A U.S. Treasurer and Public Servant | News | The Harvard Crimson. Harvard Crimson. Retrieved from http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2015/5/27/anna-cabral-1990-profile/</ref>\n* [[Shawn Camp]], baseball player, [[Toronto Blue Jays]]<ref>Fawcett, D. (March 19, 2015). Battlefield's talented trio assume new roles. Inside Nova. Retrieved from http://www.insidenova.com/sports/battlefield-s-talented-trio-assume-new-roles/article_8cdd7998-cd9d-11e4-aa61-a7a153ae66a4.html</ref>\n* [[Kathleen L. Casey]], Commissioner of the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]<ref>U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. (2008). Commissioner Kathleen L. Casey (Biography). Retrieved from https://www.sec.gov/about/commissioner/casey.htm</ref>\n* [[Rabia Chaudry]], Pakistani-American attorney, author of ''New York Times'' best-seller ''Adnan\u2019s Story: The Search for Truth and Justice After Serial'' and podcast [[Undisclosed (podcast)|host]]\n* [