u0644\u0647\u062c\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629\n|states=[[Lebanon]]\n|speakers=5.48 million\n|date=2015\n|ref=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/apc|title=Arabic, North Levantine Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref>\n|familycolor=Afroasiatic\n|fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]]\n|fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]]\n|fam4=[[Arabic]]\n|fam5=[[Levantine Arabic]]\n|fam6=[[North Levantine Arabic]]\n|listclass=hlist\n|dia1=[[Beqaa Valley|Beqaa Arabic]]\n|dia2=[[Chouf District|Iqlim-Al-Kharrub Sunni Arabic]]\n|dia3=[[Jdeideh|Jdaideh Arabic]]\n|dia4=[[Mount Lebanon Governorate|North-Central Lebanese Arabic]]\n|dia5=[[North Governorate|North Lebanese Arabic]]\n|dia6=[[Sidon|Saida Sunni Arabic]]\n|dia7=[[Lebanese Druze|South-Central Lebanese Arabic]]\n|dia8=[[Southern Lebanon|South Lebanese Arabic]]\n|dia9=[[Beirut|Sunni Beiruti Arabic]]\n|script=[[Arabic alphabet]]<br/>[[Arabic chat alphabet]]\n|isoexception=dialect\n|iso3=apc\n|glotto=stan1323\n|glottorefname=Standard Lebanese Arabic\n|notice=IPA\n|map=Lebanese Arabic Map.png\n|mapcaption=\n{{legend|#3E48CC|North Lebanese Arabic}}\n{{legend|#9AD9EA|North-Central Lebanese Arabic}}\n{{legend|#B97A57|Beqaa Arabic}}\n{{legend|#B8E714|Jdaideh Arabic}}\n{{legend|#FAC81A|Sunni Beiruti Arabic}}\n{{legend|#14B84B|South-Central Lebanese Arabic}}\n{{legend|#FDB2C7|Iqlim-Al-Kharrub Sunni Arabic}}\n{{legend|#E72121|Saida Sunni Arabic}}\n{{legend|#A24CA7|South Lebanese Arabic}}\n}}\n\n'''Lebanese Arabic''' ({{lang-ar|\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a|translit=\u02bfarabiyy lubn\u0101niyy}}, Lebanese: {{transl|apc|\u02bfarabe libn\u0113ne}}), or simply '''Lebanese''' ({{lang-ar|\u0644\u064f\u0628\u0652\u0646\u064e\u0627\u0646\u0650\u064a|translit=lubn\u0101niyy}}, Lebanese: {{transl|apc|libn\u0113ne}}), is a [[Varieties of Arabic|variety]] of [[North Levantine Arabic]], indigenous to and spoken primarily in [[Lebanon]], with significant linguistic influences borrowed from other Middle Eastern and European languages and is in some ways unique from other [[varieties of Arabic]]. Due to [[multilingualism]] among Lebanese people (a majority of the Lebanese people are bilingual or trilingual), it is not uncommon for [[Lebanese people]] to mix Lebanese Arabic, [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]] into their daily speech.\n\nLebanese Arabic has been assumed to  descend from the [[Old Arabic|Arabic dialects]] introduced to the [[Levant]] in the 7th century CE, which gradually supplanted various indigenous [[Northwest Semitic languages]] to become the regional [[lingua franca]]. As a result of this prolonged process of [[language shift]], Lebanese Arabic possesses a significant [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] [[Stratum (linguistics)#substratum|substratum]], along with later non-[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] [[Stratum (linguistics)#Adstratum|adstrate]] influences from [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]], English, and [[French language in Lebanon|French]]. As a variety of [[Levantine Arabic]], Lebanese Arabic is most closely related to [[Syrian Arabic]] and shares many [[Levantine Arabic phonology|innovations]] with [[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]] and [[Jordanian Arabic]]. However some modern researchers have opposed the idea of descendance from Peninsular Arabic dialects, such as Ahmad Al-Jallad<ref>https://www.academia.edu/38100372/Al-Jallad._A_Manual_of_the_Historical_Grammar_of_Arabic</ref> and others. These hold that the vernaculars languages went through a parallel evolution.\n\n==Differences from Standard Arabic==\nLebanese Arabic shares many features with other modern varieties of [[Arabic language|Arabic]]. Lebanese Arabic, like many other spoken Levantine Arabic varieties, has a syllable structure very different from that of [[Modern Standard Arabic]]. While Standard Arabic can have only one consonant at the beginning of a syllable, after which a vowel must follow, Lebanese Arabic commonly has two consonants in the onset.\n* Morphology: no [[Grammatical mood|mood]] or grammatical case markings.\n* Number: verbal agreement regarding number and gender is required for all subjects, whether already mentioned or not.\n* Vocabulary: many borrowings from other languages; most prominently [[Syriac language|Syriac-Aramaic]], [[Western Aramaic languages|Western-Aramaic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]], [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]], French, as well as, less significantly, from English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cometolebanon.com/about-lebanon/languages|title=Languages|website=Come To Lebanon|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n* Some authors, such as the statistician [[Nassim Nicholas Taleb]], believe that a significant part of the Lebanese grammatical structure is due to [[Aramaic]] influences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2008/Nov-25/53151-you-may-think-youre-speaking-lebanese-but-some-of-your-words-are-really-syriac.ashx|title=You may think you're speaking Lebanese, but some of your words are really Syriac|date=2008-11-25|work=The Daily Star Newspaper - Lebanon|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/east-med-project-history-philology-and-genetics/no-lebanese-is-not-a-dialect-of-arabic-e95320c164c|title=No, Lebanese is not a \u201cdialect of\u201d Arabic|last=Taleb|first=Nassim Nicholas|date=2018-01-02|website=East Med Project: History, Philology, and Genetics|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n===Examples===\n[[File:Maya Diab interview in Morocco - Oct 28, 2017.webm|thumb|An interview with Lebanese singer [[Maya Diab]]; she speaks in Lebanese Arabic.]]\n* The following example demonstrates two differences between Standard Arabic (Literary Arabic) and Spoken Lebanese Arabic: [[Coffee]] ({{lang|ar|\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629}}), Literary Arabic: {{IPA|/\u02c8qahwa/}}; Lebanese Arabic: {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0294ahwe]}}. The [[voiceless uvular plosive]] {{IPA|/q/}} corresponds to a [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[\u0294]}}, and the final vowel ({{IPA|[{{IPAplink|\u00e6}}~{{IPAplink|a}}~{{IPAplink|\u0250}}]}}) commonly written with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|t\u0101\u02be marb\u016btah}}'' ({{lang|ar|[[\u0629]]}}) is raised to {{IPAblink|e}}.\n* As a general rule, the [[voiceless uvular plosive]] {{IPA|/q/}} is replaced with [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[\u0294]}}, e.g. {{IPA|/daqi\u02d0qa/}} \"minute\" becomes {{IPA|[d\u0294i\u02d0\u0294a]}}. This [[debuccalization]] of {{IPAslink|q}} is a feature shared with  [[Syrian Arabic]], [[Palestinian Arabic]], [[Egyptian Arabic]], and [[Maltese language|Maltese]].\n* The exception for this general rule is the [[Druze]] of Lebanon who, like the Druze of [[Syria]] and [[Israel]], have retained the pronunciation of {{IPAslink|q}} in the centre of direct neighbours who have substituted the {{IPAslink|q}} for the {{IPAblink|\u0294}} (example: \"Heart\" is {{IPA|/qalb/}} in Literary Arabic, becomes {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0294aleb]}} or {{IPA|[\u0294alb]}}, which is similar in [[Syrian Arabic|Syrian]], [[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]], [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]] and [[Maltese language|Maltese]]. The use of {{IPAslink|q}} by Druze is particularly prominent in the mountains and less so in urban areas.\n* Unlike most other [[varieties of Arabic]], a few dialects of Lebanese Arabic have retained the classical diphthongs {{IPA|/aj/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} (pronounced in Lebanese Arabic as {{IPA|[e\u026a]}} and {{IPA|[e\u028a]}}<!--could a Lebanese Arabic user make sure that the previous sounds are correctly represented?-->), which were monophthongised into {{IPAblink|e\u02d0}} and {{IPAblink|o\u02d0}} elsewhere, although the majority of Lebanese Arabic dialects realize them as {{IPA|[o\u028a]}} and {{IPA|[e\u026a]}}. In urban dialects (i.e. Beiruti) {{IPAblink|e\u02d0}} has replaced {{IPA|/aj/}} and sometimes medial {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}}, and {{IPAblink|e}} has replaced final {{IPA|/i/}} making it indistinguishable with t\u0101\u02be marb\u016btah (\u0629). Also, {{IPAblink|o\u02d0}} has replaced {{IPA|/aw/}}; {{IPAblink|o}} replacing some short {{IPA|/u/}}s. In singing, the {{IPA|/aj/}}, {{IPA|/aw/}} and medial {{IPA|/a\u02d0/}} are usually maintained for artistic{{specify|date=December 2012}} values.\n* The {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} sound from Modern Standard Arabic is sometimes replaced with {{IPA|/t/}} in words from MSA like {{IPA|/\u03b8a:nija/}}, (second as in the number) when it becomes {{IPA|/te:nj\u0259/}}. Other times, it may be replaced with {{IPA|/s/}} in words like {{IPA|/\u03b8a:nija/}} (second as in the time measurement) when it becomes {{IPA|/se:nj\u0259/}}. It is assumed that this is to maintain an audible difference between the two words which were originally homophones. In some dialects, the {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} sound is replaced with {{IPA|/t/}} for both words.\n\n===Not Arabic===\n\nSeveral non-linguist commentators, including [[Nassim Taleb]], have claimed that the Lebanese vernacular is not in fact a [[variety of Arabic]] at all, but rather a separate [[Central Semitic language]] descended from older languages including [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]; those who espouse this viewpoint suggest that a large percentage of its vocabulary consists of Arabic [[loanword]]s, and that this compounds with the use of the [[Arabic alphabet]] to disguise the language's true nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/east-med-project-history-philology-and-genetics/no-lebanese-is-not-a-dialect-of-arabic-e95320c164c|title=No, Lebanese is not a \u201cdialect of\u201d Arabic|first=Nassim Nicholas|last=Taleb|date=2 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref> Taleb has recommended that the language be called Northwestern Levantine or neo-[[Canaanite language|Canaanite]].<ref>https://www.maronite-heritage.com/Lebanese%20Language.php</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phoenicia.org/leblanguage.html|title=Phoenicia: The Lebanese Language: What is the difference between the Arabic Language and the Lebanese language?|website=phoenicia.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebaneselanguage.org/language/history/|title=Lebanese Language Institute \u00bb History|website=www.lebaneselanguage.org}}</ref> Linguists reject this classification on the basis that it is easily disproved by the [[comparative method]] and other tools known to [[historical linguistics]], and that attempts to claim another ancestor for Lebanese are motivated more by [[nationalist]] politics than by a desire for linguistic impartiality.<ref>{{cite-web|url=http://lughat.blogspot.com/2014/09/why-levantine-is-arabic-not-aramaic.html|title=Jabal al-Lughat: Why \"Levantine\" is Arabic, not Aramaic: Part 1|first=Lameen Souag \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646|last=\u0633\u0648\u0627\u0642|date=7 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lughat.blogspot.com/2018/01/taleb-unintentionally-proves-lebanese.html|title=Jabal al-Lughat: Taleb unintentionally proves Lebanese comes from Arabic|first=Lameen Souag \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646|last=\u0633\u0648\u0627\u0642|date=4 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/i/moments/949816603981615110|title=Lebanese and Arabic - A Post-Mortem of the Nassim Taleb kerfuffle|website=Twitter}}</ref>. \n\nMore recently, Ahmad Al Jallad confirms that the so-called Arabic vernaculars do not descend from Arabic, but have followed a parallel evolution, what is called Classical Arabic is a more recent language with newer innovations than the so-called dialects.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/38100372/Al-Jallad._A_Manual_of_the_Historical_Grammar_of_Arabic</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\n=== Consonants ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Lebanese Arabic Consonants\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"  colspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Velar consonant|Velar/]]<br />[[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Pharyngeal consonant|Pharyngeal]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! <small>plain</small>\n! <small>[[pharyngealization|emphatic]]</small>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}} || {{IPA link|n}} || || || || ||\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stop consonant|Stop]]\n! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| ({{IPA link|p}}) || {{IPA link|t}} || {{IPA link|t\u02e4}} || ({{IPA link|t\u0361\u0283}}) || {{IPA link|k}} || || {{IPA link|\u0294}}\n|-\n! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|b}} || {{IPA link|d}} || {{IPA link|d\u02e4}} || || ({{IPA link|\u0261}}) || ||\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|f}} || {{IPA link|s}} || {{IPA link|s\u02e4}} || {{IPA link|\u0283}} || {{IPA link|x}} || {{IPA link|\u0127}} || {{IPA link|h}}\n|-\n! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| ({{IPA link|v}}) || {{IPA link|z}} || {{IPA link|z\u02e4}} || {{IPA link|\u0292}} || {{IPA link|\u0263}} || {{IPA link|\u0295}} ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Tap consonant|Tap]]/[[Trill consonant|trill]]\n| || {{IPA link|r}} || || || || ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Approximant]]\n| || {{IPA link|l}} || || {{IPA link|j}} || {{IPA link|w}} || ||\n|}\n\n*The phonemes {{IPA|/p, v/}} are not native to Lebanese Arabic and are only found in loanwords. They are sometimes realized as {{IPA|[b]}} and {{IPA|[f]}} respectively.\n*The velar stop {{IPA|/\u0261/}} occurs in native Lebanese Arabic words but is generally restricted to loanwords. It is realized as {{IPA|[k]}} by some speakers.\n\n===Vowels and diphthongs===\n[[File:Lebanese Arabic vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Lebanese Arabic vowel chart.]]\n\n==== Comparison ====\nThis table shows the correspondence between general Lebanese Arabic vowel phonemes and their counterpart realizations in Modern Standard Arabic (MSA) and other [[Levantine Arabic]] varieties.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Lebanese Arabic !! MSA !! Southern !! Central !! Northern\n|-\n| {{IPAslink|\u028c}} || [a] || [\u0251] or [\u028c] || [\u0251] or [\u028c] || [\u0254] or [e]\n|-\n| {{IPAslink|\u026a}} || [i] or [u] || [e] || [e] || [e] or [o]\n|-\n| {{IPAslink|\u028a}} || [u] || [o] or [\u028a] || [o] || [o]\n|-\n| {{IPAslink|e}}{{ref|1|1}} || [a] || [e]{{ref|1|1}} || [e]{{ref|1|1}} || [e]{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|e}}:/ || [a:] || [e:] || [e:] || [e:]\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|\u0254}}:/ || [a:] || [\u0251:] || [\u0251:] || [o:]\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|e}}:/ || [a:] || [e] || [e] || [e]\n|-\n| {{IPAslink|i}}: || [i:] || [i:] || [i:]|| [i:]\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|e}}:/ || [i] || [e] || [e] || [e] \n|-\n| /{{IPA link|u}}:/ || [u:] || [u:] || [u:] || [u:]\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|e}}{{IPA link|\u026a}}~{{IPA link|e}}:/ || [aj] || [e:] || [e:] || [e:]\n|-\n| /{{IPA link|o}}{{IPA link|\u028a}}~{{IPA link|o}}:/ || [aw] || [o:] || [o:] || [o:]\n|}\n{{note|1|1}} After back consonants this is pronounced {{IPAblink|\u028c}} in Lebanese Arabic, Central and Northern Levantine varieties, and as {{IPAblink|\u0251}} in Southern Levantine varieties\n\n<ref>Abdul-Karim, K. 1979. Aspects of the Phonology of Lebanese Arabic. University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign Doctoral Dissertation.</ref>\n\n==Regional varieties==\nAlthough there is a modern Lebanese Arabic dialect mutually understood by Lebanese people,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maronite-heritage.com/Lebanese%20Language.php|title=Lebanese Language - MARONITE HERITAGE|website=www.maronite-heritage.com|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref> there are regionally distinct variations with, at times, unique pronunciation, grammar, and vocabulary.<ref>Makki, Elrabih Massoud. 1983. The Lebanese dialect of Arabic: Southern Region. (Doctoral dissertation, Georgetown University; 155pp.)</ref>\n\nWidely used regional varieties include:\n* [[Beirut]]i varieties, further distributed according to [[Beirut#Quarters_and_sectors|neighborhoods]], the notable ones being [[Achrafieh]] variety, Basta variety, [[Ras Beirut]] variety, etc.\n* [[North Governorate|Northern varieties]], further distributed regionally, the most notable ones being [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]] variety, [[Zgharta]] variety, [[Bsharri]] variety, [[Koura District|Koura]] variety, [[Akkar District|Akkar]] variety.\n* [[Southern Lebanon|Southern]] varieties, with notable ones being the [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] and [[Bint Jbeil]] varieties.\n* [[Beqaa Valley|Beqaa]] varieties, further divided into varieties, the notable ones being [[Zahl\u00e9]] and [[Baalbek]]-[[Hermel]] varieties.\n* [[Mount Lebanon]] varieties, further divided into regional varieties like the [[Keserwan District|Keserwan]] variety, the [[Matn District|Matin]] dialect, [[Chouf District|Shouf]] variety, etc.\n\n==Writing system==\n\nLebanese Arabic is rarely written, except in [[novel]]s where a dialect is implied or in some types of [[poetry]] that do not use classical Arabic at all. Lebanese Arabic is also utilized in many Lebanese [[song]]s, theatrical pieces, local television and radio productions, and very prominently in [[zajal]].\n\nFormal publications in Lebanon, such as newspapers, are typically written in [[Modern Standard Arabic]], French, or English.\n\nWhile Arabic script is usually employed, informal usage such as [[Instant messaging|online chat]] may mix and match Latin letter [[Arabic chat alphabet|transliterations]]. The Lebanese poet [[Said Akl|Sa\u00efd Akl]] proposed the use of the Latin alphabet but did not gain wide acceptance. Whereas some works, such as ''Romeo and Juliet'' and ''Plato's Dialogues'' have been transliterated using such systems, they have not{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} gained widespread acceptance. Yet, now, most Arabic web users, when short of an Arabic keyboard, transliterate the Lebanese Arabic words in the Latin alphabet in a pattern similar to the [[Said Akl]] alphabet, the only difference being the use of digits to render the Arabic letters with no obvious equivalent in the Latin alphabet.\n\nThere is still today no generally accepted agreement on how to use the Latin alphabet to transliterate Lebanese Arabic words. However, Lebanese people are now using latin numbers while communicating online to make up for sounds not directly associable to latin letters. This is especially popular over text messages and apps such as [[WhatsApp]].\nExamples:\n* 7 for \u062d\n* 3 for \u0639\n* 2 for \u0621 or \u0642 (qaf is often pronounced as a glottal stop)\n\nIn 2010, The Lebanese Language Institute has released a Lebanese Arabic keyboard layout and made it easier to write Lebanese Arabic in a Latin script, using unicode-compatible symbols to substitute for missing sounds.<ref>Lebanese Language Institute: [http://www.lebaneselanguage.org/lll-system/lebanese-latin-letters/ Lebanese Latin Letters The Lebanese Latin Letters]</ref>\n\n===Said Akl's orthography===\n* Capitalization and punctuation are used normally the same way they are used in the French and English languages.\n* Some written consonant-letters, depending on their position, inherited a preceding vowel. As ''L'' and ''T''.\n* Emphatic consonants are not distinguished from normal ones, with the exception of {{IPA|/z\u02e4/}} represented by ''\u01b6''. Probably ''Said Akl'' did not acknowledge any other emphatic consonant.{{contradict-inline|article=Said Akl#Lebanese language and alphabet|reason=The table there contains separate letters with diacritics for all emphatics|date=June 2017}}\n* Stress is not marked.\n* Long vowels and geminated consonants are represented by double letters.\n* ''\u00c7'' which represents {{IPAslink|\u0294}} was written even initially.\n* All the [[ISO basic Latin alphabet|basic Latin alphabet]] are used, in addition to other diacriticized ones. Most of the letters loosely represent their [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] counterparts, with some exceptions:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Letter !! Corresponding phoneme(s) !! Additional information\n|-\n| a || {{IPAslink|a}}, {{IPAslink|\u0251}} || \n|-\n| aa || {{IPAslink|a\u02d0}}, {{IPAslink|\u0251\u02d0}} || \n|-\n| c || {{IPAslink|\u0283}} ||\n|-\n| \u00e7 || {{IPAslink|\u0294}} || The actual diacritic looks like a diagonal stroke on the bottom left\n|-\n| g || {{IPAslink|\u0263}} ||\n|-\n| i || {{IPAslink|\u026a}}, {{IPAslink|i}} || Represents {{IPAslink|i}} word-finally\n|-\n| ii || {{IPAslink|i\u02d0}} ||\n|-\n| j || {{IPAslink|\u0292}} ||\n|-\n| k || {{IPAslink|\u03c7}} ||\n|- \n| q || {{IPAslink|k}} ||\n|-\n| u || {{IPAslink|\u028a}}, {{IPAslink|u}} || Represents {{IPAslink|u}} word-finally\n|-\n| uu || {{IPAslink|u\u02d0}} ||\n|-\n| x || {{IPAslink|\u0127}} ||\n|-\n| y || {{IPAslink|j}} ||\n|-\n| \u0233 || {{IPAslink|\u0295}} || The actual diacritic looks like a stroke connected to the upper-left spoke of the letter\n|-\n| \u01b6 || {{IPA|/}}{{IPA link|z}}{{IPA link|\u02e4}}{{IPA|/}} ||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Varieties of Arabic]]\n* [[Levantine Arabic]]\n* [[North Levantine Arabic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Spoken Lebanese''. Maksoud N. Feghali, [[Appalachian State University]]. Parkway Publishers, 1999 ({{ISBN|978-1-887905-14-5}})\n* Michel T. Feghali, ''Syntaxe des parlers arabes actuels du Liban'', Geuthner, Paris, 1928.\n* Elie Kallas, '''Atabi Lebnaaniyyi. Un livello soglia per l'apprendimento del neoarabo libanese'', Cafoscarina, Venice, 1995.\n* Angela Daiana Langone, ''Btesem ente lebneni. Commedia in dialetto libanese di Yahya Jaber'', Universit\u00e0 degli Studi La Sapienza, Rome, 2004.\n* J\u00e9rome Lentin, \"Classification et typologie des dialectes du Bilad al-Sham\", in ''Mat\u00e9riaux Arabes et Sudarabiques'' n. 6, 1994, 11\u201343.\n* Plonka Arkadiusz, ''L\u2019id\u00e9e de langue libanaise d\u2019apr\u00e8s Sa\u2018\u012bd \u2018Aql'', Paris, Geuthner, 2004, {{ISBN|978-2-7053-3739-1}}\n* Plonka Arkadiusz, \"Le nationalisme linguistique au Liban autour de Sa\u2018\u012bd \u2018Aql et l\u2019id\u00e9e de langue libanaise dans la revue \u00abLebnaan\u00bb en nouvel alphabet\", Arabica, 53 (4), 2006, 423\u2013471.\n*Franck Salameh, \"Language, Memory, and Identity in the Middle East\", Lexington Books, 2010.\n*lebaneselanguage.org, \"Lebanese vs Arabic\", Lebanese Language Institute, March 6, 2010.\n*Abdul-Karim, K. 1979. Aspects of the Phonology of Lebanese Arabic. University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign Doctoral Dissertation.\n*Bishr, Kemal Mohamed Aly. 1956. A grammatical study of Lebanese Arabic. (Doctoral dissertation, University of London; 470pp.)\n*Choueiri, Lina. 2002. Issues in the syntax of resumption: restrictive relatives in Lebanese Arabic. Ann Arbor: UMI. (Doctoral dissertation, University of Los Angeles; xi+376pp.)\n*Makki, Elrabih Massoud. 1983. The Lebanese dialect of Arabic: Southern Region. (Doctoral dissertation, Georgetown University; 155pp.)\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Lebanese Arabic phrasebook}}\n* [https://lebanese-arabic.com Learn Arabic Lebanese with Hiba Najem]\n* [http://www.lebaneselanguage.org Lebanese Language Institute]\n* [http://www.lebaneselanguage.org/lll-system/lebanese-latin-letters/ Lebanese Arabic Latin alphabet]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324012810/http://www.decotype.com/publications/1981_RNLA-Arabic/RNLA_Lebanese_Arabic_Manual.pdf Manual with grammar of Lebanese Arabic for the Dutch UNIFIL detachment]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/LebaneseWritingRules Summary of commonly used conventions of writing the Lebanese Arabic spoken language using Latin alphabet]\n\n{{Varieties of Arabic}}\n\n[[Category:Lebanese Arabic| ]]\n[[Category:Levantine Arabic]]\n[[Category:North Levantine Arabic]]\n[[Category:Arabic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Levant]]\n", "name_user": "70.24.212.187", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebanese_Arabic"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Tingey Craven (US Navy admiral)", "text_new": "{{about|the 20th-century U.S. Navy admiral|his grandfather, also an admiral|Thomas Tingey Craven (rear admiral)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Thomas Tingey Craven\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1873|7|8}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1950|4|5|1873|7|8}}\n|image= Thomas Tingey Craven.jpg\n|caption= Lieutenant Commander Thomas Tingey Craven in service dress blue uniform.\n|nickname=\n|birth_name=\n|birth_place= [[Vallejo, California]]\n|death_place= [[St. Albans, New York]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America}}\n|branch = [[File:United States Department of the Navy Seal.svg|25px]] [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1896\u20131937,1942\u20131946\n|rank=[[File:US-O9 insignia.svg|32px]] [[Vice Admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[Director of Naval Communications]]\n|battles= [[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br />[[World War I]]<br />[[World War II]]\n|awards= [[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n\u200a'''Thomas Tingey Craven''' (8 July 1873 in [[Vallejo, California]] \u2013 5 April 1950 in [[St. Albans, New York]]) was a [[United States]] [[naval officer]] with service in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]] and rose to the rank of [[vice admiral]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was a son of [[Henry Smith Craven]], a [[United States Navy]] officer and engineer and the grandson of his namesake, [[Thomas Tingey Craven (rear admiral)|Thomas Tingey Craven]] (1808\u20131887) and great-grandson of [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] [[Thomas Tingey]] (1750\u20131829). \n\nCraven graduated from the [[United States Naval Academy]] in 1896.  His first assignment after graduation was to the newly commissioned  battleship [[USS Massachusetts (BB-2)|USS ''Massachusetts'' (BB-2)]], where he served as a naval cadet.  (Prior to the first world war, graduates of the naval academy were required to serve two years at sea prior to being commissioned.)  Craven was commissioned as an ensign on 6 May 1898.  During the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] he served on the collier [[USS Scindia|USS ''Scindia'']] which delivered coal to recently captured [[Guantanamo Bay]] in Cuba in June 1898.  He married Antoinette Merritt in 1901. \n\nIn 1908, Craven was stationed aboard the [[battleship]] {{USS|South Carolina|BB-26}} assigned duties as the ship's [[gunnery officer]]. In 1916, Thomas T. Craven was given command of the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Sacramento|PG-19|3}} which he commanded throughout World War I until 1918.\n\nIn 1919 while serving as the director of [[Naval Aviation]], Tingey ordered the {{USS|Jupiter|AC-3}}, a [[collier (ship type)|collier]], to be converted into the [[U.S. Navy]]'s first dedicated [[aircraft carrier]] which was renamed, {{USS|Langley|CV-1}}. In the aftermath of the [[Honda Point Disaster]] in September 1923, Admiral Tingey defended Captain Edward H. Watson, Commanding Officer of [[Destroyer Squadron 11]], during the [[court-martial|courts martial]] proceedings.<ref>Craven, Thomas T. (Thomas Tingey), 1873-1950. DLC. {{cite web |url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131212204604/http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml |archivedate=2013-12-12 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the remainder of his naval career, Craven commanded [[Destroyer Squadron 15]], was the [[Director of Naval Communications]], commanded [[Great Lakes Naval Training Station]], the [[Yangtze Patrol]] in China, [[Battleship Division]] One and served as the [[Commandant]] of the [[Thirteenth Naval District]] in [[Bremerton, Washington]] prior to retiring from active duty in 1937.\n\nFollowing the United States' entrance into World War II, Vice Admiral Craven was recalled to active duty serving as superintendent of the [[New York Maritime Academy]] at [[Fort Schuyler]], NY until 1946.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.whittlesey-whittelseygenealogy.com/getperson.php?personID=I2714&tree=JWhittelseyProgeny|title=Thomas Tingey CRAVEN|publisher=Whittlesey-WhittelseyFamilyHistory|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://findingaids.loc.gov/db/search/xq/searchMfer02.xq?_id=loc.mss.eadmss.ms007037&_faSection=overview&_faSubsection=did&_dmdid=|title=Thomas T. Craven papers, 1842-1969,|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml|title=Craven, Thomas T. (Thomas Tingey), 1873-1950|publisher=University of Virginia: SNAC: Social Networks and Archival Context Project|accessdate=12 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131212204604/http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml|archivedate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/3870|title=Thomas Tingey Craven, 1873-1950|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n*[https://www.usna.edu/Library/sca/man-findingaids/MS_530.EAD.xml Thomas Tingey Craven Memoirs, 1897-1953 (bulk 1942-1953), MS 530] held by Special Collections & Archives, Nimitz Library at the United States Naval Academy\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Craven, Thomas Tingey}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Navy World War II admirals]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Vallejo, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 20th-century U.S. Navy admiral|his grandfather, also an admiral|Thomas Tingey Craven (rear admiral)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Thomas Tingey Craven\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1873|7|8}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1950|4|5|1873|7|8}}\n|image= Thomas Tingey Craven.jpg\n|caption= Lieutenant Commander Thomas Tingey Craven in service dress blue uniform.\n|nickname=\n|birth_name=\n|birth_place= [[Vallejo, California]]\n|death_place= [[St. Albans, New York]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|allegiance={{flag|United States of America}}\n|branch = [[File:United States Department of the Navy Seal.svg|25px]] [[United States Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1896\u20131937,1942\u20131946\n|rank=[[File:US-O9 insignia.svg|32px]] [[Vice Admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n|unit=\n|commands=[[Director of Naval Communications]]\n|battles= [[Philippine\u2013American War]]<br />[[World War I]]<br />[[World War II]]\n|awards= [[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n\u200a'''Thomas Tingey Craven''' (8 July 1873 in [[Vallejo, California]] \u2013 5 April 1950 in [[St. Albans, New York]]) was a [[United States]] [[naval officer]] with service in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]] and rose to the rank of [[vice admiral]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was a son of [[Henry Smith Craven]], a [[United States Navy]] officer and engineer and the grandson of his namesake, [[Thomas Tingey Craven (rear admiral)|Thomas Tingey Craven]] (1808\u20131887) and great-grandson of [[Commodore (rank)|Commodore]] [[Thomas Tingey]] (1750\u20131829). \n\nCraven graduated from the [[United States Naval Academy]] in 1896.  His first assignment after graduation was to the newly commissioned  battleship [[USS Massachusetts (BB-2)|USS ''Massachusetts'' (BB-2)]], where he served as a naval cadet.  (Prior to the first world war, graduates of the naval academy were required to serve two years at sea prior to being commissioned.)  Craven was commissioned as an ensign on 6 May 1898.  During the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] he served on the collier [[USS Scindia|USS ''Scindia'']] which delivered coal to recently captured [[Guantanamo Bay]] in Cuba in June 1898.  He married Antoinette Merritt in 1901. \n\nIn 1908, Craven was stationed aboard the [[battleship]] {{USS|South Carolina|BB-26}} assigned duties as the ship's [[gunnery officer]]. In 1916, Thomas T. Craven was given command of the [[gunboat]] {{USS|Sacramento|PG-19|3}} which he commanded throughout World War I until 1918.\n\nIn 1919 while serving as the director of [[Naval Aviation]], Tingey ordered the {{USS|Jupiter|AC-3}}, a [[collier (ship type)|collier]], to be converted into the [[U.S. Navy]]'s first dedicated [[aircraft carrier]] which was renamed, {{USS|Langley|CV-1}}. In the aftermath of the [[Honda Point Disaster]] in September 1923, Admiral Tingey defended Captain Edward H. Watson, Commanding Officer of [[Destroyer Squadron 11]], during the [[court-martial|courts martial]] proceedings.<ref>Craven, Thomas T. (Thomas Tingey), 1873-1950. DLC. {{cite web |url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131212204604/http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml |archivedate=2013-12-12 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the remainder of his naval career, Craven commanded [[Destroyer Squadron 15]], was the [[Director of Naval Communications]], commanded [[Great Lakes Naval Training Station]], the [[Yangtze Patrol]] in China, [[Battleship Division]] One and served as the [[Commandant]] of the [[Thirteenth Naval District]] in [[Bremerton, Washington]] prior to retiring from active duty in 1937.\n\nFollowing the United States' entrance into World War II, Vice Admiral Craven was recalled to active duty serving as superintendent of the [[New York Maritime Academy]] at [[Fort Schuyler]], NY until 1946.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.whittlesey-whittelseygenealogy.com/getperson.php?personID=I2714&tree=JWhittelseyProgeny|title=Thomas Tingey CRAVEN|publisher=Whittlesey-WhittelseyFamilyHistory|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://findingaids.loc.gov/db/search/xq/searchMfer02.xq?_id=loc.mss.eadmss.ms007037&_faSection=overview&_faSubsection=did&_dmdid=|title=Thomas T. Craven papers, 1842-1969,|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml|title=Craven, Thomas T. (Thomas Tingey), 1873-1950|publisher=University of Virginia: SNAC: Social Networks and Archival Context Project|accessdate=12 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131212204604/http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=craven-thomas-t-thomas-tingey-1873-1950-cr.xml|archivedate=12 December 2013}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/3870|title=Thomas Tingey Craven, 1873-1950|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=12 December 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Craven, Thomas Tingey}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Philippine\u2013American War]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Navy World War II admirals]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Vallejo, California]]\n", "name_user": "Stonewall61", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Tingey_Craven_(US_Navy_admiral)"}
